\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criteria 1\'2C 3\'2C 4\'2C 5 and 7 do not comply with minimum standards. \line \line The modes of delivery indicated in the application are contact and distance. The information presented only addresses the contact mode of delivery and accreditation of the distance mode of delivery cannot be considered. \line \line The evaluator stated that the title of the programme Bachelor of Arts in Fashion Styling and Photography is unsuitable as each field \'28styling and photography\'29 is a specialist field in itself and within the clothing and fashion industry. The qualification on the NQF level 7 aims to produce fashion stylists and photographers for the fashion \'2F clothing fields. Fashion Styling falls within the ambit of fashion merchandising and marketing. Photography is a specialist field on its own. The programme as presented cannot do justice to both fields of specialization. \line \line The resourcing of the programme is insufficient. The budget of R55\'2C000.00 allocated for Fashion Styling and Photography is also the budget for 3 other programmes. Even if the budget were only used for this programme it would not be sufficiently substantial  to cater for specialist resources.\line \line The evaluator also indicated that the staff complement is unsuitably qualified in the specialist field of merchandising\'2C marketing and photography.  The SDC has 1 manager\'2C 3 full-time academic and 2 part-time academic staff members. No mention is made of support staff nor library staff for a student body of approximately 20 learners at NQF level 5 to 7. No member of staff has a pedagogical specialist qualification. No staff members have any industrial experience in Fashion Styling and Photography and none possesses qualifications \'28B Tech or equalivant\'29 at a level higher than the proposed programme i.e. BA in Fashion Styling and Photography.\line \line The SDC has in place clear policies regarding Assessment\'2C Teaching \'26 Learning\'2C Materials Development\'2C RPL\'2C Assessment and Student Admission. However\'2C no module guides\'2C assessment guides and students handbooks that serve as materials that contribute to QA were presented. No library inventory was provided. The library resource budget of R3000 is insufficient as fashion magazines\'2C periodicals\'2C academic books are extremely expensive. A comprehensive inventory of specialist learning resources for Fashion Design was not included.  The vague inventory and infrastructure that was furnished does not appear to be sufficient for a cohort of 20 students. Highly specialized resources are necessary particularly for Photography. It is not known how many computers and software are available for student use. \line \line The Directorate support the recommendation that the programme should not be accredited. \line \line \cell \pard 

